{
  "doc_id": "44962",
  "text": "Fast growth in response to strong time constraints is adaptive and common in nature (e.g. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , although it can be costly for individuals [CITATION_4] . Costs can be immediate, for example an increase in predation risk linked to higher activity [CITATION_5] , or appear later in life, for example increased oxidative stress, reduced immune function, or reduced reproductive output (e.g. [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Thus, considering the costs, it is reasonable to expect that only northern marginal populations, which are exposed to less frequent episodes of warm weather and experience overall greater time constraints than central and edge populations, will maintain plastic responses allowing maximal growth and development rates under the warmer environmental conditions.",
